BlockStmt body = new BlockStmt();
body.addStatement(Statement.createExpressedStatement(Expression.parse("System.out.println(\"Hello, World!\");")));

Alternatively, maybe using the parser to create the expression.

Let's see:

A System.out.println is an expression statement. So first, create the expression, then the statement. So, the code would be something like:

BlockStmt body = new BlockStmt();
body.addStatement(
    new ExpressionStmt(
        CompilationUnit.parse("System.out.println(\"Hello, World!\");").getResult().get().getStatement(0)
    )
); Wait, maybe that's overcomplicating.

Ah right, StaticJavaParser can be used to parse a string into a statement. So:

BlockStmt body = new BlockStmt();
body.addStatement(StaticJavaParser.parseStatement("System.out.println(\"Hello, World!\");")); Yes, that's better. So then, the BlockStmt is created, and the statement is parsed from the string. So putting it all together, the missing code for setBody would be:

new BlockStmt().addStatement(StaticJavaParser.parseStatement("System.out.println(\"Hello, World!\");")); Wait, but the setBody method takes a BlockStmt. So perhaps:

newMethod.setBody(new BlockStmt().addStatement(...));

Alternatively, create the BlockStmt first and add statements to it. Alternatively:

BlockStmt body = new BlockStmt();
body.addStatement(StaticJavaParser.parseStatement("System.out.println(\"Adding a new method!\");"));
newMethod.setBody(body); So the code inside the TODO should be:

